      "type": "Note",
      "id": "https://sarahstech.blog/comments/accessibility-comment-1",
      "published": "2025-05-15T17:30:00Z",
      "content": "Thank you for writing about this! As someone who uses a screen reader daily, I can't tell you how frustrating it is when developers treat accessibility as an afterthought. The 'beyond compliance' point is so important - WCAG is a floor, not a ceiling. Real accessibility means thinking about the user experience holistically.",
      "attributedTo": {
        "type": "Person", 
        "id": "https://mastodon.social/@a11y_advocate",
        "name": "Jordan Martinez",
        "preferredUsername": "a11y_advocate",
        "summary": "Accessibility consultant and screen reader user"
      },
      "inReplyTo": "https://sarahstech.blog/posts/web-accessibility-2025",
      "to": ["https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#Public"]
    },
    {
      "type": "Note",
      "id": "https://sarahstech.blog/comments/accessibility-reply-1",
      "published": "2025-05-15T18:15:00Z", 
      "content": "@a11y_advocate Exactly! Your perspective is so valuable here. I'd love to hear more about the specific pain points you encounter most frequently. Are there particular patterns or mistakes that developers keep making that would be easy to avoid with better awareness?",
      "attributedTo": {
        "type": "Person",
        "id": "https://sarahstech.blog/author/sarah",
        "name": "Sarah Chen",
        "preferredUsername": "sarahc"
      },
      "inReplyTo": "https://sarahstech.blog/comments/accessibility-comment-1",
      "to": ["https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#Public"],
      "tag": [
        {
          "type": "Mention",
          "href": "https://mastodon.social/@a11y_advocate",
          "name": "@a11y_advocate"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Note",
      "id": "https://sarahstech.blog/comments/accessibility-comment-2",
      "published": "2025-05-15T19:45:00Z",
      "content": "@sarahc The biggest one is probably custom components that look like standard UI elements but don't behave like them. A div that looks like a button but isn't keyboard accessible, for example. Also, developers who rely only on automated testing tools and never actually try using their app with a screen reader.",
      "attributedTo": {
        "type": "Person",
        "id": "https://mastodon.social/@a11y_advocate", 
        "name": "Jordan Martinez",
        "preferredUsername": "a11y_advocate"
      },
      "inReplyTo": "https://sarahstech.blog/comments/accessibility-reply-1",
